E, LUST AND SUFFERING IN THE ROMANCE OF THE ROSE -- tPART IV PLANTS IN MEDIEVAL BOOK DECORATION -- t12 NAMING THE FLOWERS AND PLANTS IN THE MARGINS OF LATE MEDIEVAL MANUSCRIPTS -- t13 FLOWERING MARGINS THE DEVELOPMENT OF STREWN-FLOWER BORDERS IN SOUTHERN NETHERLANDISH MANUSCRIPT ILLUMINATION -- t14 FLOWERS OF MEANING THE INTERPRETATION OF MARGINAL DECORATION IN SOUTHERN NETHERLANDISH MANUSCRIPTS FROM AROUND 1500 -- tAPPENDIX -- tAppendix I: A Hand-written Text from Late Antiquity in the Leiden University Library. The Wonders of Plantain in Apuleius Platonicus' herbarium (Leiden, UB ms VLQ 9) -- tAppendix II: A Late Medieval Printed Text in the Athenaeum Library in Deventer. Recipes in a Herb Book from 1497, the Ortus sanitatis (Deventer, AB 2000 E 45 KL) -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX OF MANUSCRIPTS CITED AND EARLY PRINTED BOOKS -- tINDEX OF INDIVIDUALS (AUTHORS, PATRONS, MAKERS AND OWNERS OF HERBARIA, ARTISTS, PRINTERS) TITLES (BOOKS, MANUSCRIPTS, HERBARIA) AND PLANTS IN CHRISTIAN ICONOGRAPHY -- tINDEX OF ENGLISH PLANT NAMES -- tLATIN NAMES FOR MEDIEVAL PLANT NAMES -- tINDEX OF LATIN PLANT NAMES -- tINDEX OF MEDIEVAL LATIN AND GREEK PLANT NAMES (ITALICS) AND (OLD) DUTCH (D.), GERMAN (G.) AND FRENCH (FR.) NAMES (ROMAN) -- tCOLOPHON0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aHow 'green' were people in late antiquity and the Middle Ages? Unlike today, the nature around them was approached with faith, trust and care. The population size was many times smaller than today and human impact on nature not as extreme as it is now. People did not have to worry about issues like deforestation and sustainability. This book is about the knowledge of plants and where that knowledge came from. How did people use earth and plants in ancient times, and what did they know about their nutritional or medicinal properties? From which plants one could make dyes, such as indigo, woad and dyer's madder? Is it possible to determine that through technical research today? Which plants could be found in a ninth-century monastery garden, and what is the symbolic significance of plants in secular and religious literature? The Green Middle Ages addresses these and other issues, including the earliest herbarium collections, with a leading role for the palaeography and beautiful illuminations from numerous medieval manuscripts kept in Dutch and other Western libraries and museums.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBotanyzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aNature and civilizationzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPlants and civilizationzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aAUP Wetenschappelijk. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aScience and Technology. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  amedieval culture, plants in medieval manuscript, artes, medieval literature, paleography, drawings of plants, the use of plants.1 aAs-Vijvers, Anne Margreet W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergen, Saskia Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiemans, Jos A.A.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriët, Jan Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChavannes-Mazel, Claudine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChavannes-Mazel, Claudine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDijkema, Annabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllers, Iris, econtribut